# Honest Feedback: This Isn't a Linked List

What you've built is essentially an **array wrapper**, not a linked list. It uses an array (`[]`) internally, which defeats the entire purpose of implementing a linked list.

## Why Does This Matter?

A linked list is a data structure where each **node** points to the next one. The key differences:

| Feature | Your Implementation | Real Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| Storage | Contiguous array | Individual nodes with pointers |
| Insertion (head) | O(n) | **O(1)** |
| Access by index | **O(1)** | O(n) |
| Memory | Pre-allocated | Allocated per node |

## What a Linked List Should Look Like

```javascript
class Node {
    constructor(data) {
        this.data = data;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

class LinkedList {
    constructor() {
        this.head = null;
        this.size = 0;
    }

    // Add to the end
    add(data) {
        const node = new Node(data);
        if (!this.head) {
            this.head = node;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            while (current.next) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            current.next = node;
        }
        this.size++;
    }

    // Remove at index
    remove(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;
        let removed;
        if (index === 0) {
            removed = this.head;
            this.head = this.head.next;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            for (let i = 0; i < index - 1; i++) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            removed = current.next;
            current.next = removed.next;
        }
        this.size--;
        return removed.data;
    }

    // Get at index
    get(index) {
        if (index < 0 || index >= this.size) return null;
        let current = this.head;
        for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) {
            current = current.next;
        }
        return current.data;
    }
}
```

## Key Differences to Notice
- **`Node` class** — each element is a self-contained object with a `next` pointer
- **Traversal** — you must walk the chain to find elements (no direct indexing)
- **Bounds checking** — prevents accessing invalid indices

## When Would You Actually Use a Linked List?
- Frequent insertions/deletions at the **head** or **middle**
- When you don't need random access
- Implementing queues, stacks, or LRU caches

Your current code works fine as a list utility — but if the goal is to learn linked lists, the node-based approach is what you want to study.
